## Error Handling

Always check errors. Use explicit ignore `_` when safe:

```go
// ✅ GOOD
result, err := operation()
if err != nil {
    return fmt.Errorf("operation failed: %w", err)
}

// ✅ GOOD - explicit ignore
_ = file.Close() // Close on read-only file

// ❌ BAD - silent ignore
result, _ := operation()
```

**Type Assertions**: Always use the two-value form:

```go
// ✅ GOOD
if handler, ok := obj.(http.Handler); ok {
    handler.ServeHTTP(w, r)
}

// ❌ BAD - can panic
handler := obj.(http.Handler)
```

<details><summary>Existing exemptions (single-value type assertions)</summary>

The following files use legacy single-value type assertions. Do not convert them
unless you are already modifying the surrounding code:

- `core/tasks/SyncVSAClusterHealthTask.go` — 12+ single-value assertions on `inputs[N].(Type)`
- `core/orchestrator/workflows/pool_workflows.go` — `args[4].(models.ResourceOperation)`
- `core/orchestrator/workflows/replicationWorkflows/hybrid_create_workflow.go` — `args[0].(replication.CreateHybridReplicationResult)`

Generated and mock files (`*_gen.go`, `*_mock.go`, `monkey_mocks*.go`) are always exempt.

</details>

## Dependency Injection

Use interfaces and dependency injection for testability:

```go
// ✅ GOOD - cloud-agnostic with DI
type PoolActivity struct {
    SE          database.Storage
    Hyperscaler hyperscaler.Services // Interface
}

func NewPoolActivity(se database.Storage, hs hyperscaler.Services) *PoolActivity {
    return &PoolActivity{SE: se, Hyperscaler: hs}
}

// ❌ BAD - direct cloud dependencies
type PoolActivity struct {
    SE         database.Storage
    IamService *iam.Service // Direct GCP dependency
}
```

<details><summary>Existing exemptions (dependency injection)</summary>

Existing activity structs access cloud services through package-level function
variables (`hyperscaler.GetGCPService(ctx)`, `hyperscaler.GetProviderByNode(ctx, node)`)
rather than injected struct fields. This is a legacy pattern — do not extend it to
new code. New activity structs and new cloud interactions should inject
`hyperscaler.Services` (or a narrower interface) as a struct field.

