## Function Design

### Decompose Large Functions

Break down monolithic functions for testability:

```go
// ✅ GOOD - decomposed
func (a *Activity) Sync(ctx context.Context, poolID int64) error {
    snapshots, err := a.getSnapshots(ctx, poolID)
    if err != nil {
        return err
    }
    return a.process(ctx, snapshots)
}

func (a *Activity) getSnapshots(ctx context.Context, poolID int64) ([]*Snapshot, error)
func (a *Activity) process(ctx context.Context, snapshots []*Snapshot) error
```

### Constructor Patterns

Provide both simple and advanced constructors:

```go
// Simple constructor with defaults
func NewActivity(se database.Storage, hs hyperscaler.Services) *Activity {
    return NewActivityWithDeps(se, hs, DefaultConfig(), DefaultDeps())
}

// Advanced constructor for testing
func NewActivityWithDeps(se database.Storage, hs hyperscaler.Services, cfg *Config, deps *Dependencies) *Activity {
    return &Activity{SE: se, Hyperscaler: hs, Config: cfg, Dependencies: deps}
}
```

## Configuration Management

Use structured config objects instead of global variables:

```go
// ✅ GOOD - structured config
type Config struct {
    ChunkSize int
    Enabled   bool
}

func DefaultConfig() *Config {
    return &Config{
        ChunkSize: env.GetInt("CHUNK_SIZE", 200),
        Enabled:   env.GetBool("ENABLED", true),
    }
}

// ❌ BAD - global variables
var (
    chunkSize = env.GetInt("CHUNK_SIZE", 200)
    enabled   = env.GetBool("ENABLED", true)
)
```

